eh\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Female Playback Singer|Best Female Playback Singer]]\n| [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] - [[Main Badhiya Tu Bhi Badhiya]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n*{{IMDb title|6452574}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|sanju}}\n*{{Mojo title|sanju}}\n*[http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/sanju/ ''Sanju''] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n\n{{Rajkumar Hirani}}\n{{A. R. Rahman}}\n{{ZeeCineAwardBestFilm}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Rajkumar Hirani]]\n[[Category:Films scored by A. R. Rahman]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:Films about Bollywood]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|For the Central Asian town and pass, see [[Sanju Pass]]. For the Indian village, see [[Sanjoo]]. For the actor also known as Sanju, see [[Sanjay Dutt]].}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sanju\n| image          = Sanju poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Rajkumar Hirani]]\n| producer       = [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]]<br />Rajkumar Hirani<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1526608/title-sanjay-dutts-biopic-revealed-simply-perfect/|title=Title of Sanjay Dutt's Biopic revealed&nbsp;\u2013 Tribune|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011215849/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1526608/title-sanjay-dutts-biopic-revealed-simply-perfect/|archivedate=11 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/see-who-visited-ranbir-kapoor-on-the-sets-of-dutt-biopic/articleshow/56793741.cms|title=See who visited Ranbir Kapoor on the sets of Dutt biopic&nbsp;\u2013 Times of India|accessdate=25 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209082530/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/see-who-visited-ranbir-kapoor-on-the-sets-of-dutt-biopic/articleshow/56793741.cms|archivedate=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n| writer         = Rajkumar Hirani<br />[[Abhijat Joshi]]\n| starring       = [[Ranbir Kapoor ]] <br />[[Paresh Rawal]]<br />[[Vicky Kaushal]]<br />[[Manisha Koirala]]<br />[[Dia Mirza]]<br/>[[Sonam Kapoor]]<br />[[Anushka Sharma]]<br />[[Jim Sarbh]]\n| Based on       = [[Sanjay Dutt]]\n| narrator       =  [[Ranbir Kapoor]]\n| cinematography = [[Ravi Varman]]\n| music          = [[A. R. Rahman]]<br />[[Rohan-Rohan]]<br />Vikram Montrose\n| editing        = Rajkumar Hirani\n| studio         = Rajkumar Hirani Films<br />[[Vinod Chopra Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Fox Star Studios]]<br />[[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|6|29|df=yes|ref1=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-the-real-reason-why-ranbir-kapoor-s-sanjay-dutt-biopic-averted-clash-with-salman-khan-s-tiger-zinda-hai-2479763|title=the real reason why Ranbir Kapoor's sanjay dutt biopic not to clash with salman khan's tiger zinda hai|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623140522/http://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-the-real-reason-why-ranbir-kapoor-s-sanjay-dutt-biopic-averted-clash-with-salman-khan-s-tiger-zinda-hai-2479763|archivedate=23 June 2017}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 161 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/amp/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/sanju-the-ranbir-kapoor-starrer-sanjay-dutt-biopic-gets-its-cbfc-rating-and-there-is-good-news-for-young-fans/244290|title=Sanju: The Ranbir Kapoor starrer Sanjay Dutt biopic gets its CBFC rating and there is good news for young fans;\u2013 Times Now News|accessdate=27 June 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627115055/https://www.timesnownews.com/amp/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/sanju-the-ranbir-kapoor-starrer-sanjay-dutt-biopic-gets-its-cbfc-rating-and-there-is-good-news-for-young-fans/244290|archivedate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR|link=yes}}150 [[crore]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/ranbir-kapoors-sanju-all-set-to-cross-200-crore-mark/article24342141.ece|title=Ranbir Kapoor's 'Sanju' all set to cross \u20b9200-crore mark|first=Deborah|last=Cornelious|date=5 July 2018|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR|586.85 [[crore]]}}<ref name=\"BH-Sanju\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Sanju''''' is a 2018 Indian [[biographical film]] directed by [[Rajkumar Hirani]] and written by Hirani and [[Abhijat Joshi]]. It was jointly produced by Hirani and [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]] under the banners Rajkumar Hirani Films and [[Vinod Chopra Films]] respectively. The film follows the life of [[Bollywood]] actor [[Sanjay Dutt]], his addiction with drugs, arrest for alleged [[1993 Bombay bombings#Sanjay Dutt and co-conspirators|association with the 1993 Bombay bombings]], relationship with his father, comeback in the industry, the eventual drop of charges from bombay blasts, and release after completing his jail term. [[Ranbir Kapoor]] stars as Dutt, along with an ensemble cast which features [[Paresh Rawal]], [[Vicky Kaushal]], [[Manisha Koirala]], [[Dia Mirza]], [[Sonam Kapoor]], [[Anushka Sharma]] and [[Jim Sarbh]].\n\nIn a conversation with Hirani, Dutt shared anecdotes from his life, which the former found intriguing and prompted him to make a film based on Dutt's life. It was titled ''Sanju'' after the nickname Dutt's mother [[Nargis]] used to call him. Principal photography began in January 2017 and was completed by January 2018. The film's soundtrack was composed by Rohan-Rohan and Vikram Montrose, with [[A. R. Rahman]] as a guest composer. [[Fox Star Studios]] acquired the distribution rights of the film.\n\n''Sanju'' was released worldwide on 29 June 2018. It received positive reviews from critics, who praised Kapoor and Kaushal's performance as well as Hirani's direction; some criticised its supposed image-cleansing of its protagonist. It registered the highest opening for any film released in India in 2018, and on its third day, it had the highest single day collection ever for a Hindi film in India. With a worldwide gross of over {{INRConvert|586.85|c}}, ''Sanju'' emerged as the [[List of Bollywood films of 2018#Box office collection|highest grossing Bollywood film of 2018]], the second [[List of highest domestic net collection of Hindi films|highest-earning Hindi film]] in India of all time, and one of the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films]].\n\n''Sanju'' earned seven nominations at the [[64th Filmfare Awards]] including [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hirani. It won [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Kapoor and [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kaushal.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film starts with D. N. Tripathi ([[Piyush Mishra]]), a lyricist, who writes a biography on [[Sanjay Dutt|Sanjay \"Sanju\" Dutt]], ([[Ranbir Kapoor]]), comparing him with [[Mahatma Gandhi]]. A flabbergasted Sanjay has him thrown out. The [[Supreme Court of India ]] delivers its verdict regarding the [[1993 Bombay bombings]] and sentences Dutt to five years jail term for violating the [[Arms Act, 1959]]. His wife [[Manyata Dutt]] ([[Dia Mirza]]) approaches Winnie Diaz, ([[Anushka Sharma]]) a London-based writer, to write Sanjay's biography and present his version of his life to the public. Although unwilling at first, Winnie is asked by Zubin Mistry ([[Jim Sarbh]]), a real estate builder, to not write the biography, which intrigues her. Winnie first interviews Sanjay, and his life is revealed in a flashback.\n\nSanjay's father [[Sunil Dutt]] ([[Paresh Rawal]]) plans to launch his acting career in [[Bollywood]] with the film ''[[Rocky (1981 film)|Rocky]]'' (1981). Upset over his father's controlling behaviour on set, Sanjay is encouraged by his friend Zubin \"God\" Mistry to try drugs for the first time. Sanjay soon discovers that his mother [[Nargis]] ([[Manisha Koirala]]) is suffering from cancer and is taken to New York for treatment. This incident furthers his descent into alcoholism and drug addiction. He meets Kamlesh ([[Vicky Kaushal]]), a fan of Nargis, in New York, and they become quick friends. Kamlesh manages to make Sanjay stay away from his addiction; after learning of his girlfriend Ruby's ([[Sonam Kapoor]]) fixed marriage due to his ongoing drug addiction, Sanjay relapses. Kamli convinces Ruby to register marry Sanjay; but when Ruby after realising her love for Sanjay, she agrees and comes to the registration office, only to find that he is not there and on reaching Sanjay's house realizes that he is still under the influence of drugs and decides to leave him. Nargis passes away three days before the release of ''Rocky'', which takes an emotional toll on Sanjay. Sanjay agrees to attend a rehabilitation centre in the United States, and eventually recovers with the help of his father and Kamlesh. On returning to India, he meets with 'God' his friend and beats him for selling him drugs. Sanjay realizes that he was given drugs while 'God' himself was consuming glucose.\n\nThe later part of Dutt's life is narrated by his now-estranged friend Kamlesh, who Winnie tracks down in New York.Kamlesh is at first reluctant since he has wasted many years of his life on Sanju but finally agrees to tell her the story. In the 1990s, Sanjay turns to bodybuilding and his career in Bollywood has greatly improved. After the 1992 [[Babri Masjid]] demolition, Sanjay acquires three [[AK-56]] rifles to ensure the protection of his father, who had by then ventured into politics, and sister, [[Priya Dutt]]. A [[1993 Bombay bombings|series of bombings occur]] in Bombay shortly thereafter. Sanjay is arrested in 1993 for possession of illegal arms supposedly supplied by the [[D-Company]] to be trafficked for protection during potential communal rioting after the bombings. Sanjay is convicted and sentenced to imprisonment for five years under [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act]] (TADA), threatening his career. Indian media labels him as a terrorist, further tarnishing his public image. Believing Sanjay to be guilty, Kamlesh severs ties with him.\n\nAfter his release in 1995, Sanjay appears in a string of flops. When his popularity had begun to wane, he is forced to sign for the [[Munna Bhai|title role]] in ''[[Munna Bhai M.B.B.S.]]'' (2003) by his father, who also features in the movie. Sanjay's performance garners him the [[Filmfare Award for Best Performance in a Comic Role]] and his public image improves, making his father proud. Shortly afterwards, his father passes away. In 2006, the Bombay High Court finds Dutt guilty under the Possession of Arms Act, while not finding him to be a terrorist. In 2013, he is arrested again by the same verdict upheld by the [[Supreme Court of India]]. Sanjay convinces Winnie and Kamlesh of his innocence by blaming the media for falsely accusing him of terrorism, and is subsequently released from prison in 2016. Sanjay finds out that Winnie has completed writing his biography, titled ''Kuch Toh Log Kahenge'' ({{translation}} People will keep saying something), named after one of his father's favourite songs from the film ''[[Amar Prem]]'' (1972). He exits the jail and reunites with Kamlesh and [[Manyata Dutt|Manyata]].\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n*[[Ranbir Kapoor]] as [[Sanjay Dutt|Sanjay \"Sanju\" Dutt]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Correspondent |first1=HT |title=From Ranbir Kapoor to Dia Mirza, a reel vs real rundown of who plays who in Sanju |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com